senses.note: Also understood as nookuu3e'ennes, plume-wing-arm ‘eagle feather arm’ (NI).

When Man makes the Sacred Wheel, he uses Long Stick (bo’ooceibiis) to make the rim [the world-circumference, Garter Snake], puts feathers from Eagle on it in four bunches, then paints celestial symbols onto it.

Buffalo robes typically had lines of porcupine quills on them as ornaments. The number of lines was fixed, and different robes were named according to the number of lines: NI neneesootoxei’i = 8-lined robe; neneesoo’ouht = 20-line robe; beeteetosoo’ouht = 100-line robe. There were rules and restrictions concerning who might 	own and wear such robes. Twenty was the normal number.
